The solution to this is to present your view controller that contains your `UITableView` or `UICollectionView` using the available `modalPresentationStyle` option full screen before you present your view controller:

```objc
yourViewController.modalPresentationStyle = UIModalPresentationFullScreen;
```

```swift
yourViewController.modalPresentationStyle = .fullScreen
```

Full example in Objective-C:


    NSString *storyboardName = @&quot;Main&quot;;
    UIStoryboard *storyboard = [UIStoryboard storyboardWithName:storyboardName bundle: nil];
    // YourViewController is the VC that contains a table view or collection view with a refresh control.
    YourViewController *vc = [storyboard instantiateViewControllerWithIdentifier:@&quot;YourViewControllerIdentifier&quot;];
    // Or not using storyboard
    // YourViewController *vc = [YourViewController new];
    vc.modalPresentationStyle = UIModalPresentationFullScreen;
    [self presentViewController:vc animated:YES completion:nil];


Experiment using the other `modalPresentationStyle` options to suit your needs. 

More information in the [Apple Docs](https://developer.apple.com/documentation/uikit/uiviewcontroller/1621355-modalpresentationstyle).

